text: Fellow Citizens of the Senate and of the House of Representatives among the vicissitude incident to life no event could have fill I with great anxiety than that of which the notification be transmit by your order and receive on the 14th day of the present month on the one hand I be summon by my Country whose voice I can never hear but with veneration and love from a retreat which I have choose with the fond predilection and in my flattering hope with an immutable decision as the asylum of my decline year a retreat which be render every day more necessary as well as more dear to I by the addition of habit to inclination and of frequent interruption in my health to the gradual waste commit on it by time on the other hand the magnitude and difficulty of the trust to which the voice of my country call I be sufficient to awaken in the wise and most experienced of her citizen a distrustful scrutiny into his qualification could not but overwhelm with despondence one who inherit inferior endowment from nature and unpractice in the duty of civil administration ought to be peculiarly conscious of his own deficiency in this conflict of emotion all I dare aver be that it have be my faithful study to collect my duty from a just appreciation of every circumstance by which it might be affect all I dare hope be that if in execute this task I have be too much sway by a grateful remembrance of former instance or by an affectionate sensibility to this transcendent proof of the confidence of my fellow citizen and have thence too little consult my incapacity as well as disinclination for the weighty and untried care before I my error will be palliate by the motive which mislead I and its consequence be judge by my country with some share of the partiality in which they originate such be the impression under which I have in obedience to the public summon repair to the present station it would be peculiarly improper to omit in this first official act my fervent supplication to that Almighty be who rule over the universe who preside in the council of nation and whose providential aid can supply every human defect that his benediction may consecrate to the liberty and happiness of the people of the United States a Government institute by themselves for these essential purpose and may enable every instrument employ in its administration to execute with success the function allot to his charge in tender this homage to the Great Author of every public and private good I assure myself that it express your sentiment not less than my own nor those of my fellow citizen at large less than either no people can be bind to acknowledge and adore the invisible Hand which conduct the affair of man more than those of the United States every step by which they have advance to the character of an independent nation seem to have be distinguish by some token of providential agency and in the important revolution just accomplish in the system of their united government the tranquil deliberation and voluntary consent of so many distinct community from which the event have result can not be compare with the mean by which most government have be establish without some return of pious gratitude along with an humble anticipation of the future blessing which the past seem to presage these reflection arise out of the present crisis have force themselves too strongly on my mind to be suppress you will join with I I trust in think that there be none under the influence of which the proceeding of a new and free government can more auspiciously commence by the article establish the executive department it be make the duty of the President to recommend to your consideration such measure as he shall judge necessary and expedient the circumstance under which I now meet you will acquit I from enter into that subject far than to refer to the great constitutional charter under which you be assemble and which in define your power designate the object to which your attention be to be give it will be more consistent with those circumstance and far more congenial with the feeling which actuate I to substitute in place of a recommendation of particular measure the tribute that be due to the talent the rectitude and the patriotism which adorn the character select to devise and adopt they in these honorable qualification I behold the sure pledge that as on one side no local prejudice or attachment no separate view nor party animosity will misdirect the comprehensive and equal eye which ought to watch over this great assemblage of community and interest so on another that the foundation of our national policy will be lay in the pure and immutable principle of private morality and the preeminence of free government be exemplify by all the attribute which can win the affection of its citizen and command the respect of the world I dwell on this prospect with every satisfaction which an ardent love for my country can inspire since there be no truth more thoroughly establish than that there exist in the economy and course of nature an indissoluble union between virtue and happiness between duty and advantage between the genuine maxim of an honest and magnanimous policy and the solid reward of public prosperity and felicity since we ought to be no less persuade that the propitious smile of Heaven can never be expect on a nation that disregard the eternal rule of order and right which Heaven itself have ordain and since the preservation of the sacred fire of liberty and the destiny of the republican model of government be justly consider perhaps as deeply as finally stake on the experiment entrust to the hand of the american people besides the ordinary object submit to your care it will remain with your judgment to decide how far an exercise of the occasional power delegate by the fifth article of the Constitution be render expedient at the present juncture by the nature of objection which have be urge against the system or by the degree of inquietude which have give birth to they instead of undertake particular recommendation on this subject in which I could be guide by no light derive from official opportunity I shall again give way to my entire confidence in your discernment and pursuit of the public good for I assure myself that whilst you carefully avoid every alteration which might endanger the benefit of an united and effective government or which ought to await the future lesson of experience a reverence for the characteristic right of freeman and a regard for the public harmony will sufficiently influence your deliberation on the question how far the former can be impregnably fortify or the latter be safely and advantageously promote to the forego observation I have one to add which will be most properly address to the House of Representatives it concern myself and will therefore be as brief as possible when I be first honor with a call into the service of my country then on the eve of an arduous struggle for its liberty the light in which I contemplate my duty require that I should renounce every pecuniary compensation from this resolution I have in no instance depart and be still under the impression which produce it I must decline as inapplicable to myself any share in the personal emolument which may be indispensably include in a permanent provision for the executive department and must accordingly pray that the pecuniary estimate for the station in which I be place may during my continuance in it be limit to such actual expenditure as the public good may be think to require having thus impart to you my sentiment as they have be awaken by the occasion which bring we together I shall take my present leave but not without resort once more to the benign Parent of the Human Race in humble supplication that since he have be pleased to favor the american people with opportunity for deliberate in perfect tranquillity and disposition for decide with unparalleled unanimity on a form of government for the security of their union and the advancement of their happiness so his divine blessing may be equally conspicuous in the enlarged view the temperate consultation and the wise measure on which the success of this government must depend

fellow citizen I be again call upon by the voice of my country to execute the function of its Chief Magistrate when the occasion proper for it shall arrive I shall endeavor to express the high sense I entertain of this distinguished honor and of the confidence which have be repose in I by the people of united America previous to the execution of any official act of the President the Constitution require an oath of office this oath I be now about to take and in your presence that if it shall be find during my administration of the Government I have in any instance violate willingly or knowingly the injunction thereof I may besides incur constitutional punishment be subject to the upbraiding of all who be now witness of the present solemn ceremony

resolution or integrity measure be pursue to concert a plan to form a more perfect union establish justice insure domestic tranquillity provide for the common defense promote the general welfare and course of these transaction I first see the Constitution of the United States in a foreign country irritated by no literary altercation animate by no public debate heat by no party animosity I read it with great satisfaction as the result of good head prompt by good heart as an experiment well adapt to the genius character situation and relation of this nation and country than any which have ever be propose or suggest in its general principle and great outline it be conformable to such a system of government as I have ever most esteemed and in some States my own native State in particular have contribute to establish claim a right of suffrage in common with my fellow citizen in the adoption or rejection of a constitution which be to rule I and my posterity as well as they and theirs I do not hesitate to express my approbation of it on all occasion in public and in private it be not then nor have be since any objection to it in my mind that the Executive and Senate be not more permanent nor have I ever entertain a thought of promote any alteration in it but such as the people themselves in the course of their experience should see and feel to be necessary or expedient and by their representative in Congress and the State legislature accord to the Constitution itself adopt and ordain return to the bosom of my country after a painful separation from it for ten year I have the honor to be elect to a station under the new order of thing and I have repeatedly lay myself under the most serious obligation to support the Constitution the operation of it have equal the most sanguine expectation of its friend and from an habitual attention to it satisfaction in its administration and delight in its effect upon the peace order prosperity and happiness of the nation I have acquire an habitual attachment to it and veneration for it what other form of government indeed can so well deserve our esteem and love there may be little solidity in an ancient idea that congregation of man into city and nation be the most pleasing object in the sight of superior intelligence but this be very certain that to a benevolent human mind there can be no spectacle present by any nation more pleasing more noble majestic or august than an assembly like that which have so often be see in this and the other Chamber of Congress of a Government in which the Executive authority as well as that of all the branch of the Legislature be exercise by citizen select at regular period by their neighbor to make and execute law for the general good can anything essential anything more than mere ornament and decoration be add to this by robe and diamond can authority be more amiable and respectable when it descend from accident or institution establish in remote antiquity than when it spring fresh from the heart and judgment of an honest and enlighten people for it be the people only that be represent it be their power and majesty that be reflect and only for their good in every legitimate government under whatever form it may appear the existence of such a government as ours for any length of time be a full proof of a general dissemination of knowledge and virtue throughout the whole body of the people and what object or consideration more pleasing than this can be present to the human mind if national pride be ever justifiable or excusable it be when it spring not from power or rich grandeur or glory but from conviction of national innocence information and benevolence in the midst of these pleasing idea we should be unfaithful to ourselves if we should ever lose sight of the danger to our liberty if anything partial or extraneous should infect the purity of our free fair virtuous and independent election if an election be to be determine by a majority of a single vote and that can be procure by a party through artifice or corruption the Government may be the choice of a party for its own end not of the nation for the national good if that solitary suffrage can be obtain by foreign nation by flattery or menace by fraud or violence by terror intrigue or venality the Government may not be the choice of the american people but of foreign nation it may be foreign nation who govern we and not we the people who govern ourselves and candid man will acknowledge that in such case choice would have little advantage to boast of over lot or chance such be the amiable and interesting system of government and such be some of the abuse to which it may be expose which the people of America have exhibit to the admiration and anxiety of the wise and virtuous of all nation for eight year under the administration of a citizen who by a long course of great action regulate by prudence justice temperance and fortitude conduct a people inspire with the same virtue and animate with the same ardent patriotism and love of liberty to independence and peace to increase wealth and unexampled prosperity have merit the gratitude of his fellow citizen command the high praise of foreign nation and secure immortal glory with posterity in that retirement which be his voluntary choice may he long live to enjoy the delicious recollection of his service the gratitude of mankind the happy fruit of they to himself and the world which be daily increase and that splendid prospect of the future fortune of this country which be open from year to year his
